Docker 1/6

? What is docker = an application that helps  manage , ship , scale and develop you apps in containers 

- Docker engine = portable , lightweight app runtime + packaging tool - responsible for creating containers based off instructions in docker file and images 

- Docker Hub = cloud service (an App Store for images) for sharing applications & automating workflows 


Images 

? What are images = templates for creating containers ( snapshot of app at a point in time ) that don’t change 
( change only via recreating image)

Docker file -> Docker image (template runs as) -> docker container 

*Docker file are instructions on how to build your docker image to run as a container*


Containers 

? What are containers:

-  Running instances ( different versions of the same app - dev , test , production) of images 
-  Lightweight , portable units that package up everything (dependancies like libraries & code ) for app 
-  Run consistently across different env’s - due to isolation  
-  Can start , stop & modify 


? What’s the importance of containers = they make apps portable and consistent 
- Can run a container on your laptop , test server or cloud with no changes 


Structure: 

Docker container 1 , 2 , 3          = indépendant , standalone containers with apps inside + respective dependancies 
^
Docker Engine                       = manages the containers 
^
Host operating system               = Mac OS , Linux etc 
^ 
Infrastructure                      = physical server , cloud VM , Laptop 


? Benefits of Containers: 

- Each isolated with their own consistent environments -  preventing conflicts + smooth running 
( apps works on different developers laptops because the app has all the needed dependencies in the container )

- Deployment more predictable + reliable 
- Resource efficient because they share the same kernel as the operating system 


Virtual machines 

Virtual machine:
- Allows multiple operating systems to run on a single physical machine , being more resource heavy too 

Structure: 

Virtual machines                     = VM gets to run its own guest OS on the same physical machines resources + has dependancies to run
^
hypervisor  (virtualisation)         = lets VM’S run divides up physcial hardware an allocates chunks to vm’s so they run (cpu/memory)
^
Host operating system                = Mac OS , Linux etc 
^ 
Infrastructure (physical/virtual)    = physical server , cloud VM , Laptop 


Containers Vs VM’s

VM’s : 
- Run full guest OS with allocated resources from physical machine 
- Heavier + slow to start due to emulating full hardware 
- Good for running multiple OS on the same physical system 

Containers: 
- Run docker image (snapshot) of app + share host OS kernel so less resource heavy 
- Fewer resources used vs VM’s
- Good for deploying apps in a consistent environment and way on different physical machines 


Importance in modern devops 

- Simplified deployment - package up dependancies and deploy anywhere 
- Improved efficiency - resource efficiency 
- Enhanced collaboration - docker image shared & no complex env set up
